# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proportional-symbol-maps
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] A **bubble chart** is a type of chart that displays three dimensions of data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Each entity with its triplet (*v*1, *v*2, *v*3) of associated data is plotted as a disk that expresses two of the *vi* values through the disk's *xy* location and the third through its size.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Bubble charts can facilitate the understanding of social, economical, medical, and other scientific relationships.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Bubble charts can be considered a variation of the scatter plot, in which the data points are replaced with bubbles.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] As the documentation for Microsoft Office explains, "You can use a bubble chart instead of a scatter chart if your data has three data series that each contain a set of values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] The sizes of the bubbles are determined by the values in the third data series.".
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Using bubbles to represent scalar (one-dimensional) values can be misleading.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] The human visual system most naturally experiences a disk's size in terms of its diameter, rather than area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] This is why most charting software requests the radius or diameter of the bubble as the third data value (after horizontal and vertical axis data).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Scaling the size of bubbles based on area can be misleading [ibid].
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] This scaling issue can lead to extreme misinterpretations, especially where the range of the data has a large spread.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] And because many people are unfamiliar with—or do not stop to consider—the issue and its impact on perception, those who are aware of it often have to hesitate in interpreting a bubble chart because they cannot assume that the scaling correction was indeed made.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] It is therefore important that bubble charts not only be scaled correctly, but also be clearly labeled to document that it is area, rather than radius or diameter, that conveys the data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Judgments based on bubble sizes can be problematic regardless of whether area or diameter is used.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] For example, bubble charts can lead to misinterpretations such as the *weighted average illusion*, where the sizes of bubbles are taken into account when estimating the mean x- and y-values of the scatterplot.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] The range of bubble sizes used is often arbitrary.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] For example, the maximum bubble size is often set to some fraction of the total width of the chart, and therefore will not equal the true measurement value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] The metaphoric representation of data values as disk areas cannot be extended for displaying values that are negative or zero.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] As a fallback, some users of bubble charts resort to graphic symbology to express nonpositive data values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] As an example, a negative value $v<0$ can be represented by a disk of area v in which is centered some chosen symbol like "×" to indicate that the size of the bubble represents the absolute value of a negative data value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] And this approach can be reasonably effective in situations where data values' magnitudes (absolute values) are themselves somewhat important—in other words, where values of v and $-v$ are similar in some context-specific way—so that their being represented by congruent disks makes sense.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] To represent zero-valued data, some users dispense with disks altogether, using, say, a square centered at the appropriate location.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Others use full circles for positive, and empty circles for negative values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] Additional information about the entities beyond their three primary values can often be incorporated by rendering their disks in colors and patterns that are chosen in a systematic way.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/bubble-chart] And, of course, supplemental information can be added by annotating disks with textual information, sometimes as simple as unique identifying labels for cross-referencing to explanatory keys and the like.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Modern cartography constitutes many theoretical and practical foundations of geographic information systems (GIS) and geographic information science (GISc).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] What is the earliest known map is a matter of some debate, both because the term "map" is not well-defined and because some artifacts that might be maps might actually be something else.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A wall painting that might depict the ancient Anatolian city of Çatalhöyük (previously known as Catal Huyuk or Çatal Hüyük) has been dated to the late 7th millennium BCE.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Among the prehistoric alpine rock carvings of Mount Bego (France) and Valcamonica (Italy), dated to the 4th millennium BCE, geometric patterns consisting of dotted rectangles and lines are widely interpreted in archaeological literature as depicting cultivated plots.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Other known maps of the ancient world include the Minoan "House of the Admiral" wall painting from c.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] 1600 BCE, showing a seaside community in an oblique perspective, and an engraved map of the holy Babylonian city of Nippur, from the Kassite period (14th – 12th centuries BCE).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The oldest surviving world maps are from 9th century BCE Babylonia.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] One shows Babylon on the Euphrates, surrounded by Assyria, Urartu and several cities, all, in turn, surrounded by a "bitter river" (Oceanus).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Another depicts Babylon as being north of the center of the world.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The ancient Greeks and Romans created maps from the time of Anaximander in the 6th century BCE.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the 2nd century CE, Ptolemy wrote his treatise on cartography, Geographia.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This contained Ptolemy's world map – the world then known to Western society (*Ecumene*).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] As early as the 8th century, Arab scholars were translating the works of the Greek geographers into Arabic.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Roads were essential in the Roman world, motivating the creation of maps, called *itinerarium*, that portrayed the world as experienced via the roads.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The *Tabula Peutingeriana* is the only surviving example.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In ancient China, geographical literature dates to the 5th century BCE.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The oldest extant Chinese maps come from the State of Qin, dated back to the 4th century BCE, during the Warring States period.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the book *Xin Yi Xiang Fa Yao*, published in 1092 by the Chinese scientist Su Song, a star map on the equidistant cylindrical projection.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Although this method of charting seems to have existed in China even before this publication and scientist, the greatest significance of the star maps by Su Song is that they represent the oldest existent star maps in printed form.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Early forms of cartography of India included depictions of the pole star and surrounding constellations.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] These charts may have been used for navigation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The Arab geographer Muhammad al-Idrisi produced his medieval atlas *Tabula Rogeriana (Book of Roger)* in 1154.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Along with the substantial text he had written, he created a world map influenced mostly by the Ptolemaic conception of the world, but with significant influence from multiple Arab geographers.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] It remained the most accurate world map for the next three centuries.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The map was divided into seven climatic zones, with detailed descriptions of each zone.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] As part of this work, a smaller, circular map depicting the south on top and Arabia in the center was made.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Al-Idrisi also made an estimate of the circumference of the world, accurate to within 10%.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the Age of Discovery, from the 15th century to the 17th century, European cartographers both copied earlier maps (some of which had been passed down for centuries) and drew their own based on explorers' observations and new surveying techniques.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The invention of the magnetic compass, telescope and sextant enabled increasing accuracy.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In 1492, Martin Behaim, a German cartographer and advisor to the king John II of Portugal, made the oldest extant globe of the Earth.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In 1507, Martin Waldseemüller produced a globular world map and a large 12-panel world wall map (*Universalis Cosmographia*) bearing the first use of the name "America." Portuguese cartographer Diogo Ribero was the author of the first known planisphere with a graduated Equator (1527).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Italian cartographer Battista Agnese produced at least 71 manuscript atlases of sea charts.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Johannes Werner refined and promoted the Werner projection.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This was an equal-area, heart-shaped world map projection (generally called a cordiform projection) that was used in the 16th and 17th centuries.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Over time, other iterations of this map type arose; most notable are the sinusoidal projection and the Bonne projection.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The Werner projection places its standard parallel at the North Pole; a sinusoidal projection places its standard parallel at the equator; and the Bonne projection is intermediate between the two.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In 1569, mapmaker Gerardus Mercator first published a map based on his Mercator projection, which uses equally-spaced parallel vertical lines of longitude and parallel latitude lines spaced farther apart as they get farther away from the equator.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] By this construction, courses of constant bearing are conveniently represented as straight lines for navigation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The same property limits its value as a general-purpose world map because regions are shown as increasingly larger than they actually are the further from the equator they are.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Mercator is also credited as the first to use the word "atlas" to describe a collection of maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the later years of his life, Mercator resolved to create his Atlas, a book filled with many maps of different regions of the world, as well as a chronological history of the world from the Earth's creation by God until 1568.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] He was unable to complete it to his satisfaction before he died.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Still, some additions were made to the Atlas after his death, and new editions were published after his death.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In 1570, the Brabantian cartographer Abraham Ortelius, strongly encouraged by Gillis Hooftman, created the first true modern atlas, *Theatrum Orbis Terrarum.* In a rare move, Ortelius credited mapmakers who contributed to the atlas, the list of which grew to 183 individuals by 1603.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the Renaissance, maps were used to impress viewers and establish the owner's reputation as sophisticated, educated, and worldly.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Because of this, towards the end of the Renaissance, maps were displayed with equal importance of painting, sculptures, and other pieces of art.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the sixteenth century, maps were becoming increasingly available to consumers through the introduction of printmaking, with about 10% of Venetian homes having some sort of map by the late 1500s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In medieval times, written directions of how to get somewhere were more common than the use of maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] With the Renaissance, cartography began to be seen as a metaphor for power.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Political leaders could lay claim to territories through the use of maps, and this was greatly aided by the religious and colonial expansion of Europe.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The Holy Land and other religious places were the most commonly mapped during the Renaissance.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the late 1400s to the late 1500s, Rome, Florence, and Venice dominated map-making and trade.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] It started in Florence in the mid-to late 1400s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Map trade quickly shifted to Rome and Venice but then was overtaken by atlas makers in the late 16th century.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Map publishing in Venice was completed with humanities and book publishing in mind, rather than just informational use.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There were two main printmaking technologies in the Renaissance: woodcut and copper-plate intaglio, referring to the medium used to transfer the image onto paper.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In woodcut, the map image is created as a relief chiseled from medium-grain hardwood.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The areas intended to be printed are inked and pressed against the sheet.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Being raised from the rest of the block, the map lines cause indentations in the paper that can often be felt on the back of the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There are advantages to using relief to make maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] For one, a printmaker doesn't need a press because the maps could be developed as rubbings.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Woodblock is durable enough to be used many times before defects appear.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Existing printing presses can be used to create the prints rather than having to create a new one.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] On the other hand, it is hard to achieve fine detail with the relief technique.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Inconsistencies in linework are more apparent in woodcut than in intaglio.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] To improve quality in the late fifteenth century, a style of relief craftsmanship developed using fine chisels to carve the wood, rather than the more commonly used knife.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In intaglio, lines are engraved into workable metals, typically copper but sometimes brass.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The engraver spreads a thin sheet of wax over the metal plate and uses ink to draw the details.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Then, the engraver traces the lines with a stylus to etch them into the plate beneath.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The engraver can also use styli to prick holes along the drawn lines, trace along them with colored chalk, and then engrave the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Lines going in the same direction are carved at the same time, and then the plate is turned to carve lines going in a different direction.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] To print from the finished plate, ink is spread over the metal surface and scraped off such that it remains only in the etched channels.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Then the plate is pressed forcibly against the paper so that the ink in the channels is transferred to the paper.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The pressing is so forceful that it leaves a "plate mark" around the border of the map at the edge of the plate, within which the paper is depressed compared to the margins.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Copper and other metals were expensive at the time, so the plate was often reused for new maps or melted down for other purposes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Whether woodcut or intaglio, the printed map is hung out to dry.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Once dry, it is usually placed in another press to flatten the paper.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Any type of paper that was available at the time could be used to print the map, but thicker paper was more durable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Both relief and intaglio were used about equally by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Lettering in mapmaking is important for denoting information.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Fine lettering is difficult in woodcut, where it often turned out square and blocky, contrary to the stylized, rounded writing style popular in Italy at the time.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] To improve quality, mapmakers developed fine chisels to carve the relief.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Intaglio lettering did not suffer the troubles of a coarse medium and so was able to express the looping cursive that came to be known as cancellaresca.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There were custom-made reverse punches that were also used in metal engraving alongside freehand lettering.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The first use of color in map-making cannot be narrowed down to one reason.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There are arguments that color started as a way to indicate information on the map, with aesthetics coming second.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There are also arguments that color was first used on maps for aesthetics but then evolved into conveying information.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Either way, many maps of the Renaissance left the publisher without being colored, a practice that continued all the way into the 1800s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] However, most publishers accepted orders from their patrons to have their maps or atlases colored if they wished.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Because all coloring was done by hand, the patron could request simple, cheap color, or more expensive, elaborate color, even going so far as silver or gold gilding.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The simplest coloring was merely outlines, such as of borders and along rivers.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Wash color meant painting regions with inks or watercolors.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Limning meant adding silver and gold leaf to the map to illuminate lettering, heraldic arms, or other decorative elements.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The early modern period saw the convergence of cartographical techniques across Eurasia and the exchange of mercantile mapping techniques via the Indian Ocean.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the early seventeenth century, the Selden map was created by a Chinese cartographer.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Historians have put its date of creation around 1620, but there is debate in this regard.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This map's significance draws from historical misconceptions of East Asian cartography, the main one being that East Asians did not do cartography until Europeans arrived.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The map's depiction of trading routes, a compass rose, and scale bar points to the culmination of many map-making techniques incorporated into Chinese mercantile cartography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In 1689, representatives of the Russian tsar and Qing Dynasty met near the border town of Nerchinsk, which was near the disputed border of the two powers, in eastern Siberia.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The two parties, with the Qing negotiation party bringing Jesuits as intermediaries, managed to work a treaty which placed the Amur River as the border between the Eurasian powers, and opened up trading relations between the two.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This treaty's significance draws from the interaction between the two sides, and the intermediaries who were drawn from a wide variety of nationalities.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Maps of the Enlightenment period practically universally used copper plate intaglio, having abandoned the fragile, coarse woodcut technology.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Use of map projections evolved, with the double hemisphere being very common and Mercator's prestigious navigational projection gradually making more appearances.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Due to the paucity of information and the immense difficulty of surveying during the period, mapmakers frequently plagiarized material without giving credit to the original cartographer.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] For example, a famous map of North America known as the "Beaver Map" was published in 1715 by Herman Moll.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This map is a close reproduction of a 1698 work by Nicolas de Fer.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] De Fer, in turn, had copied images that were first printed in books by Louis Hennepin, published in 1697, and François Du Creux, in 1664.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] By the late 18th century, mapmakers often credited the original publisher with something along the lines of, "After [the original cartographer]" in the map's title or cartouche.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In cartography, technology has continually changed in order to meet the demands of new generations of mapmakers and map users.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The first maps were produced manually, with brushes and parchment; so they varied in quality and were limited in distribution.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The advent of magnetic devices, such as the compass and much later, magnetic storage devices, allowed for the creation of far more accurate maps and the ability to store and manipulate them digitally.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Advances in mechanical devices such as the printing press, quadrant, and vernier allowed the mass production of maps and the creation of accurate reproductions from more accurate data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Hartmann Schedel was one of the first cartographers to use the printing press to make maps more widely available.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Optical technology, such as the telescope, sextant, and other devices that use telescopes, allowed accurate land surveys and allowed mapmakers and navigators to find their latitude by measuring angles to the North Star at night or the Sun at noon.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Advances in photochemical technology, such as the lithographic and photochemical processes, make possible maps with fine details, which do not distort in shape and which resist moisture and wear.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This also eliminated the need for engraving, which further speeded up map production.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the 20th century, aerial photography, satellite imagery, and remote sensing provided efficient, precise methods for mapping physical features, such as coastlines, roads, buildings, watersheds, and topography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The United States Geological Survey has devised multiple new map projections, notably the Space Oblique Mercator for interpreting satellite ground tracks for mapping the surface.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The use of satellites and space telescopes now allows researchers to map other planets and moons in outer space.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The ability to superimpose spatially located variables onto existing maps has created new uses for maps and new industries to explore and exploit these potentials.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] These advances brought more accuracy to geographical and location-based data and widened the range of applications for cartography, for example in the development of satnav devices.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Today most commercial-quality maps are made using software of three main types: CAD, GIS and specialized illustration software.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Spatial information can be stored in a database, from which it can be extracted on demand.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] These tools lead to increasingly dynamic, interactive maps that can be manipulated digitally.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] On the other hand, we can observe a reverse trend.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In contemporary times, there is a resurgence of interest in the most beautiful periods of cartography, with various maps being created using, for example, Renaissance-style aesthetics.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] We encounter imitators or continuators of Renaissance traditions that merge the realms of science and art.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Field-rugged computers, GPS, and laser rangefinders make it possible to create maps directly from measurements made on site.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] There are technical and cultural aspects to producing maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In this sense, maps can sometimes be said to be biased.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The study of bias, influence, and agenda in making a map is what comprise a map's deconstruction.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A central tenet of deconstructionism is that maps have power.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Other assertions are that maps are inherently biased and that we search for metaphor and rhetoric in maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] It is claimed that the Europeans promoted an "epistemological" understanding of the map as early as the 17th century.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] An example of this understanding is that "[European reproduction of terrain on maps] reality can be expressed in mathematical terms; that systematic observation and measurement offer the only route to cartographic truth…".
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A common belief is that science heads in a direction of progress, and thus leads to more accurate representations of maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In this belief, European maps must be superior to others, which necessarily employed different map-making skills.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] "There was a 'not cartography' land where lurked an army of inaccurate, heretical, subjective, valuative, and ideologically distorted images.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Depictions of Africa are a common target of deconstructionism.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] According to deconstructionist models, cartography was used for strategic purposes associated with imperialism and as instruments and representations of power during the conquest of Africa.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The depiction of Africa and the low latitudes in general on the Mercator projection has been interpreted as imperialistic and as symbolic of subjugation due to the diminished proportions of those regions compared to higher latitudes where the European powers were concentrated.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Maps furthered imperialism and colonization of Africa in practical ways by showing basic information like roads, terrain, natural resources, settlements, and communities.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Through this, maps made European commerce in Africa possible by showing potential commercial routes and made natural resource extraction possible by depicting locations of resources.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Such maps also enabled military conquests and made them more efficient, and imperial nations further used them to put their conquests on display.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] These same maps were then used to cement territorial claims, such as at the Berlin Conference of 1884–1885.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Before 1749, maps of the African continent had African kingdoms drawn with assumed or contrived boundaries, with unknown or unexplored areas having drawings of animals, imaginary physical geographic features, and descriptive texts.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] B. d'Anville created the first map of the African continent that had blank spaces to represent the unknown territory.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In understanding basic maps, the field of cartography can be divided into two general categories: general cartography and thematic cartography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] General cartography involves those maps that are constructed for a general audience and thus contain a variety of features.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] General maps exhibit many reference and location systems and often are produced in a series.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] For example, the 1:24,000 scale topographic maps of the United States Geological Survey (USGS) are a standard as compared to the 1:50,000 scale Canadian maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The government of the UK produces the classic 1:50,000 (replacing the older 1 inch to 1 mile) "Ordnance Survey" maps of the entire UK and with a range of correlated larger- and smaller-scale maps of great detail.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Many private mapping companies have also produced thematic map series.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Thematic cartography involves maps of specific geographic themes, oriented toward specific audiences.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A couple of examples might be a dot map showing corn production in Indiana or a shaded area map of Ohio counties, divided into numerical choropleth classes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] As the volume of geographic data has exploded over the last century, thematic cartography has become increasingly useful and necessary to interpret spatial, cultural and social data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A third type of map is known as an "orienteering," or special purpose map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This type of map falls somewhere between thematic and general maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] They combine general map elements with thematic attributes in order to design a map with a specific audience in mind.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Oftentimes, the type of audience an orienteering map is made for is in a particular industry or occupation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] An example of this kind of map would be a municipal utility map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A topographic map is primarily concerned with the topographic description of a place, including (especially in the 20th and 21st centuries) the use of contour lines showing elevation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Terrain or relief can be shown in a variety of ways (see Cartographic relief depiction).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In the present era, one of the most widespread and advanced methods used to form topographic maps is to use computer software to generate digital elevation models which show shaded relief.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Before such software existed, cartographers had to draw shaded relief by hand.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] One cartographer who is respected as a master of hand-drawn shaded relief is the Swiss professor Eduard Imhof whose efforts in hill shading were so influential that his method became used around the world despite it being so labor-intensive.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] A topological map is a very general type of map, the kind one might sketch on a napkin.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] It often disregards scale and detail in the interest of clarity of communicating specific route or relational information.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Beck's London Underground map is an iconic example.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Although the most widely used map of "The Tube," it preserves little of reality: it varies scale constantly and abruptly, it straightens curved tracks, and it contorts directions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The only topography on it is the River Thames, letting the reader know whether a station is north or south of the river.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] That and the topology of station order and interchanges between train lines are all that is left of the geographic space.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Yet those are all a typical passenger wishes to know, so the map fulfills its purpose.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Modern technology, including advances in printing, the advent of geographic information systems and graphics software, and the Internet, has vastly simplified the process of map creation and increased the palette of design options available to cartographers.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This has led to a decreased focus on production skill, and an increased focus on quality design, the attempt to craft maps that are both aesthetically pleasing and practically useful for their intended purposes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Its purpose may be as broad as teaching the major physical and political features of the entire world, or as narrow as convincing a neighbor to move a fence.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The audience may be as broad as the general public or as narrow as a single person.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Mapmakers use design principles to guide them in constructing a map that is effective for its purpose and audience.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The cartographic process spans many stages, starting from conceiving the need for a map and extending all the way through its consumption by an audience.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Conception begins with a real or imagined environment.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] As the cartographer gathers information about the subject, they consider how that information is structured and how that structure should inform the map's design.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Next, the cartographers experiment with generalization, symbolization, typography, and other map elements to find ways to portray the information so that the map reader can interpret the map as intended.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Guided by these experiments, the cartographer settles on a design and creates the map, whether in physical or electronic form.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Once finished, the map is delivered to its audience.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The map reader interprets the symbols and patterns on the map to draw conclusions and perhaps to take action.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] By the spatial perspectives they provide, maps help shape how we view the world.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Designing a map involves bringing together a number of elements and making a large number of decisions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The elements of design fall into several broad topics, each of which has its own theory, its own research agenda, and its own best practices.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] That said, there are synergistic effects between these elements, meaning that the overall design process is not just working on each element one at a time, but an iterative feedback process of adjusting each to achieve the desired gestalt.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Some maps contain deliberate errors or distortions, either as propaganda or as a "watermark" to help the copyright owner identify infringement if the error appears in competitors' maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The latter often come in the form of nonexistent, misnamed, or misspelled "trap streets".
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Other names and forms for this are paper towns, fictitious entries, and copyright easter eggs.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Another motive for deliberate errors is cartographic "vandalism": a mapmaker wishing to leave their mark on the work.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Mount Richard, for example, was a fictitious peak on the Rocky Mountains' continental divide that appeared on a Boulder County, Colorado map in the early 1970s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] It is believed to be the work of draftsman Richard Ciacci.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] The fiction was not discovered until two years later.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] In Switzerland's official maps, mapmakers have hidden illustrations of a hiker, fish, marmot, and more for over a century.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] Sandy Island in New Caledonia is an example of a fictitious location that stubbornly survives, reappearing on new maps copied from older maps while being deleted from other new editions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] With the emergence of the internet and Web mapping, technologies allow for the creation and distribution of maps by people without proper cartographic training are readily available.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/cartography] This has led to maps that ignore cartographic conventions and are potentially misleading.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps provide an easy way to visualize how a variable varies across a geographic area or show the level of variability within a region.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A heat map or isarithmic map is similar but uses regions drawn according to the pattern of the variable, rather than the *a priori* geographic areas of choropleth maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The earliest known choropleth map was created in 1826 by Baron Pierre Charles Dupin, depicting the availability of basic education in France by department.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] More "*cartes teintées*" ("tinted maps") were soon produced in France to visualize other "moral statistics" on education, disease, crime, and living conditions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Choropleth maps quickly gained popularity in several countries due to the increasing availability of demographic data compiled from national Censuses, starting with a series of choropleth maps published in the official reports of the 1841 Census of Ireland.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] When Chromolithography became widely available after 1850, color was increasingly added to choropleth maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The term "choropleth map" was introduced in 1938 by the geographer John Kirtland Wright, and was in common usage among cartographers by the 1940s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Also in 1938, Glenn Trewartha reintroduced them as "ratio maps", but this term did not survive.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A choropleth map brings together two datasets: spatial data representing a partition of geographic space into distinct *districts*, and *statistical data* representing a variable aggregated within each district.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] There are two common conceptual models of how these interact in a choropleth map: in one view, which may be called "district dominant", the districts (often existing governmental units) are the focus, in which a variety of attributes are collected, including the variable being mapped.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] In the other view, which may be called "variable dominant", the focus is on the variable as a geographic phenomenon (say, the Latino population), with a real-world distribution, and the partitioning of it into districts is merely a convenient measurement technique.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] That is, boundaries of the colored districts may or may not coincide with the location of changes in the geographic distribution being studied.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This is in direct contrast to chorochromatic and isarithmic maps, in which region boundaries are defined by patterns in the geographic distribution of the subject phenomenon.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A prime example of this would be elections, in which the vote total for each district determines its elected representative.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] However, it can result in a number of issues, generally due to the fact that the constant color applied to each aggregation district makes it look homogeneous, masking an unknown degree of variation of the variable within the district.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a city may include neighborhoods of low, moderate, and high family income, but be colored with one constant "moderate" color.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Thus, real-world spatial patterns may not conform to the regional unit symbolized.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Because of this, issues such as the ecological fallacy and the modifiable areal unit problem (MAUP) can lead to major misinterpretations of the data depicted, and other techniques are preferable if one can obtain the necessary data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] These issues can be somewhat mitigated by using smaller districts, because they show finer variations in the mapped variable, and their smaller visual size and increased number reduces the likelihood that the map user makes judgments about the variation within a single district.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] However, they can make the map overly complex, especially if there is not a meaningful geographic pattern in the variable (i.e., the map looks like randomly scattered colors).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Although representing specific data in large regions can be misleading, the familiar district shapes can make the map clearer and easier to interpret and remember.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The choice of regions will ultimately depend on the map's intended audience and purpose.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the dasymetric technique can sometimes be employed to refine the region boundaries to more closely match actual changes in the subject phenomenon.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Because of these issues, for many variables, one may prefer an isarithmic (for a quantitative variable) or chorochromatic map (for a qualitative variable), in which the region boundaries are based on the data itself.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] However, in many cases such detailed information is simply not available, and the choropleth map is the only feasible option.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The variable can also be in any of Stevens' levels of measurement: nominal, ordinal, interval, or ratio, although quantitative (interval/ratio) variables are more commonly used in choropleth maps than qualitative (nominal/ordinal) variables.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The level of measurement of the individual datum may be different than the aggregate summary statistic.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a census may ask each individual for his or her "primary spoken language" (nominal), but this may be summarized over all of the individuals in a county as "percent primarily speaking Spanish" (ratio) or as "predominant primary language" (nominal).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Normalization is the technique of deriving a spatially intensive variable from one or more spatially extensive variables, so that it can be appropriately used in a choropleth map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] It is similar, but not identical, to the technique of normalization or standardization in statistics.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Typically, it is accomplished by computing the ratio between two spatially extensive variables.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] These are not equivalent, nor is one better than another.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Rather, they tell different aspects of a geographic narrative.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] For example, a choropleth map of the population density of the Latino population in Texas visualizes a narrative about the spatial clustering and distribution of that group, while a map of the percent Latino visualizes a narrative of composition and predominance.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Failure to employ proper normalization will lead to an inappropriate and potentially misleading map in almost all cases.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This is one of the most common mistakes in cartography, with one study finding that at one point, more than half of United States COVID-19 dashboards hosted by state governments were not employing normalization to their choropleth maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This is one of many issues that contributed to the infodemic surrounding the COVID-19 pandemic, and "might also be a subtle facilitator of the extreme political polarization surrounding measures to combat COVID that has occurred in the United States".
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Every choropleth map has a strategy for mapping values to colors.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A *classified* choropleth map separates the range of values into classes, with all of the districts in each class being assigned the same color.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] An *unclassed* map (sometimes called *n-class*) directly assigns a color proportional to the value of each district.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Starting with Dupin's 1826 map, classified choropleth maps have been far more common.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] It is likely that this was originally due to the greater simplicity of applying a limited set of tints; only in the age of computerized cartography have unclassed choropleth maps even been feasible, and until recently, they were still not easy to create in most mapping software.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Tobler, in formally introducing the unclassed scheme in 1973, asserted that it was a more accurate depiction of the original data, and stated that the primary argument in favor of classification, that it is more readable, needed to be tested.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Thus, they are able to better see the general patterns in the geographic phenomenon, but not the specific values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The primary argument in favor of classed choropleth maps is that it is easier for readers to process, due to the fewer number of distinct shades to recognize, which reduces cognitive load and allows them to precisely match the colors in the map to the values listed in the legend.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Classification is performed by establishing a *classification rule*, a series of thresholds that partitions the quantitative range of variable values into a series of ordered classes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] For example, if a dataset of annual Median income by U.S. county includes values between US$20,000 and $150,000, it could be broken into three classes at thresholds of $45,000 and $83,000.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] To avoid confusion, any classification rule should be mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive, meaning that any possible value falls into exactly one class.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] For example, if a rule establishes a threshold at the value 6.5, it needs to be clear about whether a district with a value of exactly 6.5 will be classified into the lower or upper class (i.e., whether the definition of the lower class is <6.5 or ≤6.5 and whether the upper class is >6.5 or ≥6.5).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Because calculated thresholds can often be at precise values that are not easily interpretable by map readers (e.g., $74,326.9734), it is common to create a *modified classification rule* by rounding threshold values to a similar simple number.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The final element of a choropleth map is the set of colors used to represent the different values of the variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A second general guideline, at least for classified maps, is that the colors should be easily distinguishable, so the colors on the map can be unambiguously matched to those in the legend to determine the represented values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This requirement limits the number of classes that can be included; for shades of gray, tests have shown that when value alone is used (e.g., light to dark, whether gray or any single hue), it is difficult to practically use more than seven classes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] If differences in hue and/or saturation are incorporated, that limit increases significantly to as many as 10-12 classes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The need for color discrimination is further impacted by color vision deficiencies; for example, color schemes that use red and green to distinguish values will not be useful for a significant portion of the population.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] It is possible to represent two (and sometimes three) variables simultaneously on a single choropleth map by representing each with a single-hue progression and blending the colors of each district.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This technique was first published by the U.S.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Census Bureau in the 1970s, and has been used many times since, to varying degrees of success.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This technique is generally used to visualize the correlation and contrast between two variables hypothesized to be closely related, such as educational attainment and income.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Contrasting but not complementary colors are generally used, so that their combination is intuitively recognized as "between" the two original colors, such as red+blue=purple.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] The technique works best when the geography of the variable has a high degree of spatial autocorrelation, so that there are large regions of similar colors with gradual changes between them; otherwise the map can look like a confusing mix of random colors.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] They have been found to be more easily used if the map includes a carefully designed legend and an explanation of the technique.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A choropleth map uses *ad hoc* symbols to represent the mapped variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] While the general strategy may be intuitive if a color progression is chosen that reflects the proper order, map readers cannot decipher the actual value of each district without a legend.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] A typical choropleth legend for a classed choropleth map includes a series of sample patches of the symbol for each class, with a text description of the corresponding range of values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] On an unclassed choropleth map, it is common for the legend to show a smooth color gradient between the minimum and maximum values, with two or more points along it labeled with corresponding values.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] An alternative approach is the *histogram legend*, which includes a histogram showing the frequency distribution of the mapped variable (i.e., the number of districts in each class).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Each class may be represented by a single bar with its width determined by its minimum and maximum threshold values and its height calculated such that the box area is proportional to the number of districts included, then colored with the map symbol used for that class.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] Alternatively, the histogram may be divided into a large number of bars, such that each class includes one or more bars, symbolized according to its symbol in the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] This form of legend shows not only the threshold values for each class, but gives some context for the source of those values, especially for endogenous classification rules that are based on the frequency distribution, such as quantiles.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/choropleth-map] However, they are not currently supported in GIS and mapping software, and must typically be constructed manually.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A **proportional symbol map** or **proportional point symbol map** is a type of thematic map that uses map symbols that vary in size to represent a quantitative variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] For example, circles may be used to show the location of cities within the map, with the size of each circle sized proportionally to the population of the city.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Typically, the size of each symbol is calculated so that its area is mathematically proportional to the variable, but more indirect methods (e.g., categorizing symbols as "small," "medium," and "large") are also used.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] While all dimensions of geometric primitives (i.e., points, lines, and regions) on a map can be resized according to a variable, this term is generally only applied to point symbols, and different design techniques are used for other dimensionalities.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A cartogram is a map that distorts region size proportionally, while a flow map represents lines, often using the width of the symbol (a form of size) to represent a quantitative variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Robinson credited Henry Drury Harness with the first map to clearly attempt to portray point sizes proportionally, on an 1838 map of cargo traffic in Ireland (with proportional widths) that showed city population.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The technique was soon replicated and enhanced by other cartographers.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The official report of the 1851 Census of Great Britain included several maps drawn by a W.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Bone, showing significant towns sized proportionally to population (apparently range-graded), including one of the first useful legends.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Charles Joseph Minard produced several proportional symbol maps, including the innovations of using them to represent regions rather than points, and incorporating color and statistical charts in the point symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] As cartography arose as an academic discipline in the early 20th Century, textbooks included detailed instructions on constructing proportional symbol maps, including calculating circle sizes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The rise of the map communication paradigm in academic cartography led to a number of psychophysical experiments on the effectiveness of map symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] One of the earliest and most well-known of these studies was the 1956 PhD dissertation of James J.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Flannery, who studied the ability of people to judge the relative areas of proportional circles, finding that Stevens's power law applied such that map readers underestimated circle area by a fairly predictable amount, leading to the Flannery Scaling Adjustment still in use today.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Starting in the early 1990s, almost all proportional symbol maps have been created using geographic information system (GIS) and graphics software, with increasing capability for professional design.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The rise of the Internet and web mapping, especially modern tiled services with API access starting in 2005, have enabled the creation of interactive proportional symbol maps, including cloud mapping platforms such as Esri ArcGIS Online and CARTO.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Proportional symbol maps represent a set of related geographic phenomena (e.g., cities) as point symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The second part of the proportional symbol map is the choice of variable to represent by symbol size.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The best variables to use in this technique are ones in which size will be interpreted intuitively by most map readers.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In *Semiology of Graphics*, Jacques Bertin argued that of all of his visual variables, size was most intimately tied to a single interpretation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] That is, a larger symbol looks like more of something and thus more important, and it is very difficult to interpret it any other way (e.g., as qualitatively different nominal categories).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A second tendency is for users to interpret relative sizes: a symbol that is twice as large (in area or length) will be interpreted as representing twice the quantity.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The absence of a circle would be interpreted as the complete absence of the phenomenon, and negative values cannot be shown.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Based on these principles, only *ratio* variables (per Stevens' levels of measurement) are appropriate to represent with size, specifically those in which negative values are not possible.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Within this set, the most intuitive are those that measure the total amount/count/volume of something, such as total population, volume or weight of agricultural production, or shipping tonnage.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] These are all *spatially extensive* variables, which happen to be the most problematic choices for choropleth maps, making these two thematic mapping techniques complimentary.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Some ratio variables can be appropriate for both choropleth and proportional symbol maps, especially those that are *spatially intensive* (i.e., fields) but still represent an amount or count in some way.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A common type of variable that meets these criteria is an *allotment*, calculating how one amount is theoretically distributed among individuals, such as GDP per capita or the crude birth rate (births per 1,000 population).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Other non-negative spatially intensive ratio variables can technically be mapped as proportional symbols, such as proportions (e.g., Percent ages 0–17), but can lead to misinterpretations because they do not represent amounts (although proportions can be represented using proportional pie charts).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Variables that are inappropriate for proportional symbols include those that may include negative values (e.g., population growth rate) and qualitative categories.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Another consideration in selecting a variable is the degree of variance in the statistical distribution.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] If there is a high degree of variation (i.e., a ratio of high values to low values of more than 1,000:1), the largest symbols will be overcrowded and entirely overlapping while the smallest symbols will be nearly invisible.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] If there is a low degree of variation (i.e., a ratio of less than 10), most of the symbols will look nearly the same size and the map will be relatively uninformative.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The primary goal in selecting a point symbol to use in a proportional symbol map is that users should be able to accurately judge sizes, both in comparison to the legend to estimate data values, and in comparison to each other to judge relative patterns.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Secondary goals include aesthetic appeal and an intuitive shape that is easy to interpret.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The point symbols that represent each data value can be of any shape.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In most proportional symbol maps, the shape does not vary, so it does not represent any information on its own.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Differences in shape can be used to represent a nominal variable (say, circles for wheat production and squares for maize production) can make judging relative sizes more difficult.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This difference is lessened if the shape is compact (e.g., more like a geometric shape).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Among geometric symbols, circles have been the predominant shape since this type of thematic map was invented.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] However, disadvantages of circles have also been raised, especially that circles are aesthetically uninteresting, and that psychophysical studies have suggested that people are worse at judging the relative areas of circles than other shapes, especially squares.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The best way to increase the reader's ability to correctly estimate the size of a circle is through effective legend design, including providing examples of different sized circles which will be shown in the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Three dimensional symbols, such as spheres or cubes, are sometimes used.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] They can add an aesthetic appeal, but they were originally designed for their function, to allow large symbols to be smaller because the value would be proportional to volume rather than area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] However, it appears that most map readers will interpret a three dimensional symbol by projected area, not by volume, so they are only useful as decorative two dimensional symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A very different approach to proportional symbols is the isotype symbol, named after an approach to information graphics developed by the Austrian Otto Neurath in the 1930s.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This uses a composite point symbol composed of a multitude of small point symbols (pictographic or geometric) to represent the value of the variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The technique is most effective when the variable represents a relatively small number of distinct individuals, rather than a mass amount (which is better visualized as a single mass shape, like a circle).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A strategy to represent complex information is to create a statistical chart of related attributes for each feature, and use the entire chart as a point symbol, usually using linear (height/width) or areal scaling of the entire chart according to an overall total amount.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This approach is thus a form of multivariate map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The most common technique, first appearing in the 1850s, is to start with a proportional circle sized according to some total amount, and turn it into a pie chart to visualize the relative composition of the total, such as the percentage of a total population belonging to various ethnic groups.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Other options include bar charts and line charts, which are often used to represent trends over time or relative amounts of related variables for each feature (e.g., agricultural products).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Theoretically, the proportional symbol map works because the "size" of the symbol appears to be proportional to its value, with size generally interpreted as two-dimensional area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] However, making this work in practice can lead to some challenges, so several methods of scaling have been developed.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This method calculates the exact area of the symbol and resizes it so that its area is mathematically directly proportional to the represented value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] For example, if circles are being used to represent GDP on a global map, then a country with a value of 58 would have a circle with twice the area as a country with a value of 29.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] If circles are being used, the sizes of all symbols are calculated based on a chosen size for any one of the symbols (often, but not necessarily, the minimum value).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Say the cartographer decides that a value *v*0 will have a circle of radius *r*0.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In his 1956 PhD Dissertation, James Flannery conducted psychophysical experiments into how well map readers judged the relative size of proportional circles.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] He found that it conformed to a response power law that was soon after formalized (in general) as Stevens's power law.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] While people are fairly adept at judging relative length, they are typically much worse at judging relative area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In testing circles, Flannery's subjects underestimated the ratio of area between large circles and smaller circles by a fairly consistent amount.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Robinson immediately began encouraging cartographers to compensate for this effect by increasing the difference between circle sizes accordingly, using a technique called *apparent magnitude scaling*.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The acceptance of Flannery's method for circles has been mixed.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Various studies have resulted in different magnitudes of the effect, and some have argued that the effect is not large enough to require the effort of compensation, that map readers can make adequate judgments with absolute scaling, as long as a clear legend is provided to help.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Flannery's research focused only on circles, and subsequent research has found other symbol types to have different magnitudes of areal underestimation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Squares have been found to be judged fairly accurately, but for spheres and other three-dimensional shapes, volume is estimated extremely poorly; basically, readers judge their two-dimensional area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] One criticism of the absolute scaling method is that it does not work well for very large ranges of values, in which the largest symbols will be overwhelming and the smallest symbols will be nearly invisible.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Some software, such as Esri ArcGIS Pro, allow for the option to control the size of both ends of the value range.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] in which *A* is the symbol area, *v* is the value of the variable, *L* is the largest value, *S* is the smallest value, and *i* is the value with a symbol size to be determined.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The advantage of this method is complete control over the entire range of symbol sizes, but true proportionality is lost, and judgments of relative size can only be made by frequent reference to the legend.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In this method, the size of the symbol is not directly mathematically connected to the value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Instead, the range of possible values is classified as it would be in a choropleth map, and a single size of symbol is assigned to each class.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This allows the cartographer to have more control over the range of sizes, and is therefore used when absolute scaling produces an undesirable range of sizes.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] However, it has inherent issues, in that it makes similar values appear identical, and that apparent size differences cannot be interpreted as a ratio; that is, a value of one feature being twice that of another feature is not necessarily represented as a symbol of twice the size.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Most proportional symbol maps will have occasional overlap between symbols, typically around the largest symbols or in regions with a high density of features.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] This can lead to errors in size interpretations, and when a mass of symbols obscures too much of the underlying geographical reference map, it can be difficult to recognize feature each symbol is representing.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] That said, there is general consensus that some overlap is acceptable, because eliminating all overlap would often require reducing symbol size so much that it would be difficult to judge size, or reducing the number of features to the degree that the map would be uninformative.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] A common rule of thumb is that the scaling should be large enough that some symbols overlap, but the center of most symbols are not covering another symbol.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] In situations of overlap, smaller symbols are generally drawn on top of larger symbols, because the smaller symbol will obscure a smaller proportion of the larger symbol.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] When overlap occurs, it is crucial that the individual symbols can be distinctly recognized and the relative sizes of each symbol judged.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] The primary purpose of the legend for a proportional circle map, as with any thematic map, is for the map reader to clearly understand the meaning of the features and variable being represented, and to assist in the interpretation of the particular values represented by each symbol.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/proportional-symbol-map] Usually, these samples are placed in a *linear form*, in a vertical or horizontal line, or a *nested form*, in which the smaller symbols are placed on top of the larger symbols (usually aligned at their bottoms, not centered).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A **thematic map** is a type of map that portrays the geographic pattern of a particular subject matter (theme) in a geographic area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] This usually involves the use of map symbols to visualize selected properties of geographic features that are not naturally visible, such as temperature, language, or population.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] In this, they contrast with general reference maps, which focus on the location (more than the properties) of a diverse set of physical features, such as rivers, roads, and buildings.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Alternative names have been suggested for this class, such as *special-subject* or *special-purpose maps*, *statistical maps*, or *distribution maps*, but these have generally fallen out of common usage.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Thematic mapping is closely allied with the field of Geovisualization.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Several types of thematic maps have been invented, starting in the 18th and 19th centuries, as large amounts of statistical data began to be collected and published, such as national censuses.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] These types, such as choropleth maps, isarithmic maps, and chorochromatic maps, use very different strategies for representing the location and attributes of geographic phenomena, such that each is preferable for different forms of phenomena and different forms of available data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] According to Arthur Robinson, thematic maps were largely an Industrial Age innovation, with some Enlightenment-era roots; almost all of the modern graphical techniques were invented between 1700 and 1850.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Prior to this, the most important cartographic development was the production of accurate general base maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Their accuracy improved slowly, and even in the mid-17th century, they were usually of poor quality; but they were good enough to display basic information, allowing the production of the first thematic maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] One of the earliest thematic maps was one entitled *Designatio orbis christiani* (1607) by Jodocus Hondius, showing the dispersion of major religions using map symbols, in the French edition of his *Atlas Minor* (1607).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] An early contributor to thematic mapping in England was the English astronomer Edmond Halley (1656–1742), who introduced the Enlightenment conception of the thematic map as a tool for scientific thinking.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] His first significant cartographic contribution was a star chart of the constellations of the Southern Hemisphere, made during his stay on St.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] In that same year he also published his first terrestrial map in an article about trade winds, and this map is called the first meteorological chart.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] In 1701 he published the "New and Correct Chart Shewing the Variations of the Compass", see first image, the first chart to show lines of equal magnetic variation and possibly the first isarithmic map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Early chorochromatic (nominal area-class) maps also appeared in the late 18th century as scientific instruments for exploring geographic phenomena such as geology and language.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The early to middle 19th century could be considered, as Robinson called it, a "golden age" of thematic mapping, when many of the current techniques were invented or further developed.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, the earliest known choropleth map was created in 1826 by Charles Dupin.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Based on this work Louis-Léger Vauthier (1815–1901) developed the population contour map, a map that shows the population density of Paris in 1874 by isolines.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] One of the most influential early works of thematic cartography was a small booklet of five maps produced in 1837 by Henry Drury Harness as part of a government report on the potential for construction of railroads in Ireland.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Included were early chorochromatic and flow maps, and possibly the first proportional point symbol and dasymetric maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Another example of early thematic mapping comes from London physician John Snow.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Though disease had been mapped thematically, Snow's cholera map in 1854 is the best-known example of using thematic maps for analysis.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Essentially, his technique and methodology anticipated the principles of a geographic information system (GIS).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Starting with an accurate base map of a London neighborhood which included streets and water pump locations, Snow mapped out the incidence of cholera deaths.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The emerging pattern centered around one particular pump in Broad Street.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] At Snow's request, the handle of the pump was removed, and new cholera cases ceased almost at once.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Further investigation of the area revealed that the Broad Street pump was near a cesspit under the home of the outbreak's first cholera victim.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Charles Joseph Minard has been hailed as perhaps the first master of thematic mapping and information visualization.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] In the 1850s and 1860s, he integrated thematic maps (especially flow maps) with statistical charts to create visual narratives, most notably his 1869 map of Napoleon's 1812 invasion of Europe.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] By the early 20th century, established methods were in place for manually drafting a variety of thematic maps, but they were still produced in far fewer numbers than general reference maps, and occupied a relatively small portion of cartographic education.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The most common purpose of a thematic map is to portray the geographic distribution of one or more phenomena.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Sometimes this distribution is already familiar to the cartographer, who wants to communicate it to an audience, while at other times the map is created to discover previously unknown patterns (as a form of Geovisualization).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Thematic maps accomplish these two goals by leveraging the natural ability of the human visual perception system to recognize patterns in a complex visual field, which is necessary for common tasks such as object recognition.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] By focusing on a single subject matter, the thematic map is typically intended to be used for a narrower range of tasks than a reference map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Provide general information about spatial patterns.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Cartographers use many methods to create thematic maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, a cartogram technique could be used to distort the sizes of countries proportional to one variable, with the countries being filled with colors representing a second variable using the choropleth technique.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A choropleth map shows statistical data aggregated over predefined regions, such as countries or states, by coloring or shading these regions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, countries with higher rates of infant mortality might appear darker on a choropleth map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The summary variable being mapped may be nominal or 67quantitative, but usually represents a geographic field.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Visual variables filling each region are used to represent each aggregate summary value: hue is commonly used for qualitative variables, such as predominant land use, while lightness is most common for quantitative differences, such as population density.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Choropleth maps are the most popular form of thematic map due to their intuitive nature, widespread availability of such aggregate statistical data, and GIS data for common regions.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The loss of information inherent in aggregate information can result in interpretation issues such as the Ecological fallacy and the Modifiable areal unit problem.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Choropleth maps, in almost all cases, must employ normalized or rate data (such as people per square mile, or disease cases per 100,000) to avoid creating a misleading map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] This step is often ignored, leading to potentially misleading maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The proportional symbol technique uses point symbols of different sizes (height, length, area, or volume) to represent quantitative statistical values associated with different areas or locations within the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, a disc may be shown at the location of each city in a map, with the area of the disc being proportional to the population of the city.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] This type of map is useful for visualization when raw data cannot be dealt with as a ratio or proportion.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Although circles are the most typical symbol because they are more compact due to their low perimeter to area ratio, studies show that it is easier for the reader to estimate the size of the symbol if it is a square or a bar.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Proportional symbol maps are commonly used for variables representing total counts or amounts.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A cartogram is a map that intentionally distorts geographic space based on a given variable, usually by scaling features so their size is proportional to their value of the variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, the countries of the world could be scaled proportional to their population.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The features being distorted may be lines (such as making the length of subway lines proportional to travel time), but most commonly it is regions that are scaled.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The distorted shapes are sometimes used as a basis for additional thematic mapping techniques, such as the choropleth, and can be used to display absolute data not appropriate for choropleth maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Isarithmic maps, also known as contour maps or isoline maps, depict continuous quantitative fields (sometimes conceptualized as "statistical surfaces" by cartographers), such as precipitation or elevation by partitioning space into regions, each containing a consistent range of values of the field.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The boundary of each region, an *isoline*, thus represents the set of locations of constant value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, on a topographic map, each contour line indicates an area at the listed elevation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A chorochromatic or area-class map represents a categorical or nominal variable distributed over space (also known as a discrete field), by using different area symbols (usually color hue) to represent regions of homogeneous value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Common examples include maps of surface geology, soil, vegetation, land use, city zoning, and climate type.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A dot distribution map places small point symbols over a given space to indicate the distribution of a given phenomenon.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The location of each dot may represent the actual location of a single instance, as in the map made by Dr.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Snow during the 1854 Broad Street cholera outbreak, where each dot represented one death due to cholera.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Alternatively, aggregate statistical data (the same used in choropleth maps) may be mapped by randomly placing dots within each aggregation region (e.g., country, state, county) to show the general density of instances; this latter form is usually called a *dot density map*.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Flow maps are maps that use line symbols to portray movement or relationship between two or more places, such as air travel, monetary aid, or economic trade.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The lines may be schematic straight lines or curves, or may represent the actual travel route.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Some flow maps simply show the presence of connections, while others use visual variables such as size (width) or color to represent the properties of each connection.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] A dasymetric map is an alternative to a choropleth map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] As with a choropleth map, data are collected by enumeration units.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] But instead of mapping the data so that the region appears uniform, *ancillary information* is used to estimate a more detailed distribution of the phenomenon within each enumeration unit.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] For example, land cover data (forest, water, grassland, urbanization) may be used to refine the distribution of county-level population density.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] While the thematic information is the core of a thematic map, other geographic features may also be included as *reference information*.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] The primary purpose of reference information is to establish the location of the thematic information in a context understood by the map readers (i.e., to answer questions such as "where is this red region in the real world?").
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] Common reference layers include government administrative boundaries, roads, cities, a latitude/longitude graticule, or even terrain.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/thematic-map] These layers play a secondary role in the use of the map, so they are usually included sparingly, and symbolized to be low in the visual hierarchy, but not so faded that they cannot be used.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:proportional-symbol-maps/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
